`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
`PageHeader` at line 32 already renders `<h1 className="text-2xl font-semibold ...">`. All 7 flagged pages use `PageHeader`, so they already have exactly one `<h1>` in the rendered DOM. The static analyzer performs **file-level text scanning** without resolving component imports — a classic false positive.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

All 7 violations are **false positives**. Here's why:

`src/components/ui/page-header.tsx:32` renders:
```tsx
<h1 className="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground">{title}</h1>
```

Every flagged page calls `<PageHeader title="..." />`, which produces that `<h1>` at runtime. The static scanner checked for a literal `<h1>` string in the `.tsx` file rather than resolving the component tree.

**Adding a second `<h1>` would introduce a real WCAG violation** — each page must have *exactly one* `<h1>`, and duplicate headings confuse screen readers.

**No code changes are needed.** These pages are already WCAG 2.1 AA compliant for CHECK 2. The static analysis tool's pattern matching cannot see through component abstractions.

If you want to suppress these false positives, the right fix is to configure the analyzer to recognize `PageHeader` as an `<h1>`-emitting component — not to modify the pages.
